Ares Scout: Mars Sample Return Rover

Type: robotic | Generated: 12/6/2025

Executive Summary

A compact, six-wheeled autonomous rover designed for geological exploration and sample collection on the Martian surface. It features a collapsible rocker-bogie suspension system to fit within a 1-meter cubic volume for transport, deploying to a larger footprint for stability on loose regolith. It is equipped with a 5-DOF robotic arm utilizing a percussive coring drill and a deployable solar array for power generation.

#include 

// Pin Definitions
const int ACTUATOR_DEPLOY_PIN = 10;
const int LIMIT_SWITCH_STOWED = 11;
const int LIMIT_SWITCH_DEPLOYED = 12;
const int WHEEL_MOTORS[6] = {2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7};

// System Constraints
const float MAX_VOLUME_DIMENSION = 1.0; // meters
const float MAX_SLIP_RATIO = 0.20; // 20% slip limit for soft sand

enum RoverState {
  STOWED,
  DEPLOYING,
  DEPLOYED,
  FAULT
};

class RoverMobilitySystem {
private:
  RoverState currentState;
  float currentSlipRatio;
  
  // Simulated sensor reading for actual velocity vs wheel velocity
  float getActualGroundSpeed() {
    // In production, this comes from Visual Odometry or IMU integration
    return 0.0; 
  }

  float getWheelLinearSpeed() {
    // Average RPM of 6 wheels converted to m/s
    return 0.0;
  }

public:
  RoverMobilitySystem() : currentState(STOWED), currentSlipRatio(0.0) {}

  void init() {
    for(int i=0; i<6; i++) pinMode(WHEEL_MOTORS[i], OUTPUT);
    pinMode(ACTUATOR_DEPLOY_PIN, OUTPUT);
    pinMode(LIMIT_SWITCH_STOWED, INPUT_PULLUP);
    pinMode(LIMIT_SWITCH_DEPLOYED, INPUT_PULLUP);
  }

  // Expands rocker-bogie from 1m^3 box to operational footprint
  bool deploySystem() {
    if (currentState != STOWED) return false;

    digitalWrite(ACTUATOR_DEPLOY_PIN, HIGH);
    currentState = DEPLOYING;

    // Blocking deployment sequence (simplified for snippet)
    unsigned long startTime = millis();
    while (digitalRead(LIMIT_SWITCH_DEPLOYED) != LOW) {
      if (millis() - startTime > 30000) {
        currentState = FAULT;
        digitalWrite(ACTUATOR_DEPLOY_PIN, LOW);
        return false; // Deployment timed out
      }
      delay(10);
    }

    digitalWrite(ACTUATOR_DEPLOY_PIN, LOW);
    currentState = DEPLOYED;
    return true;
  }

  // Drive logic with traction control for Martian regolith
  void updateDrive(float targetSpeed, float turnRate) {
    if (currentState != DEPLOYED) {
      stopMotors();
      return; // Safety interlock: cannot drive if stowed
    }

    float wheelSpeed = getWheelLinearSpeed();
    float groundSpeed = getActualGroundSpeed();
    
    // Calculate Slip Ratio: (WheelSpeed - GroundSpeed) / WheelSpeed
    if (wheelSpeed > 0.01) {
      currentSlipRatio = (wheelSpeed - groundSpeed) / wheelSpeed;
    } else {
      currentSlipRatio = 0.0;
    }

    // Traction Control: Reduce power if slip exceeds 20%
    float tractionFactor = 1.0;
    if (currentSlipRatio > MAX_SLIP_RATIO) {
      tractionFactor = 1.0 - (currentSlipRatio - MAX_SLIP_RATIO);
      if (tractionFactor < 0.0) tractionFactor = 0.0;
    }

    applyMotorPower(targetSpeed * tractionFactor, turnRate);
  }

  void applyMotorPower(float speed, float turn) {
    // Differential drive or Ackerman logic applied to 6 wheels
    // Simplified PWM output
    int pwmValue = (int)(speed * 255);
    for(int i=0; i<6; i++) {
        analogWrite(WHEEL_MOTORS[i], constrain(pwmValue, 0, 255));
    }
  }

  void stopMotors() {
    for(int i=0; i<6; i++) analogWrite(WHEEL_MOTORS[i], 0);
  }
};

RoverMobilitySystem rover;

void setup() {
  rover.init();
}

Validation Checks

  • Inconsistent Solar Array Constraints: Parts List specifies 'Quantity: 2' with '2m diameter' each, but Diagram Description describes a single 'circular pattern'. Two 2m arrays plus chassis would physically exceed the 1m stowage volume constraint. Corrected to Quantity: 1 (Deck-mounted Petal array).
  • Unrealistic Battery Capacity: 100Ah is excessively heavy for a 150kg solar-powered rover (e.g., Curiosity is ~900kg with ~80Ah; MER was ~185kg with ~16Ah). Reduced to 50Ah to align with mass constraints.
  • Tribology/Lubrication Error: 'Wet lubrication prohibited' is technically incorrect. Space mechanisms (sealed harmonic drives) rely on low-outgassing greases (e.g., Braycote). Constraint clarified to prohibit 'exposed' wet lubrication only.
  • Budget Underestimation: $50M-$150M is unrealistic for a flight-grade Mars Sample Return rover. Adjusted range to $200M-$500M for vehicle hardware development.
